Player RED is offering 10 dollars, which is a relatively small fraction of their total resources (100). Since there are no future games and rejecting would result in both losing everything, it is optimal to accept this offer.

From a rational perspective, BLUE has no resources to trade and no leverage. Accepting the offer secures at least some value (10 dollars) rather than risking nothing by rejecting. Since BLUE cannot propose any trade, accepting is the only logical move to maximize their gain in this one-time interaction.

Additionally, if BLUE rejects, they get nothing, and RED loses nothing but walks away. This is a classic ultimatum game scenario, where rejecting small offers is irrational if the alternative is zero. BLUE has no incentive to punish RED for a low offer because there is no future retaliation or bargaining.

